To convert markdown formatted text to html, we first need to remove all non-alphanumeric characters, and then convert the remaining characters to html entities. This can be done using the `stripos` function in C++.

Here is the function you can use to convert markdown formatted text to html:

```cpp
void toHtml(string& text, const char* encoding)
{
    string htmlText;
    char[] line;
    int lineCount;

    // Remove non-alphanumeric characters
    lineCount = text.size();
    char[] line = text;

    for (int i = 0; i < lineCount; ++i)
        char c = text[i];

        if (c >= '0' && c <= '9') {
            line[i] = c;
        } else if (c >= 'A' && c <= 'F') {
            line[i] = c;
        } else if (c >= 'a' && c <= 'f') {
            line[i] = c;
        } else if (c >= '0' && c <= '9') {
            line[i] = '0' + c;
        } else if (c >= 'A' && c <= 'F') {
            line[i] = c + 'A' + '0';
        } else if (c >= 'a' && c <= 'f') {
            line[i] = c + 'A' + 'a' + '0';
        } else if (c >= '0' && c <= '9') {
            line[i] = c + '0' + '0';
        } else {
            line[i] = c;
        }
    }

    htmlText = string::from(char[0], line, lineCount);
    return htmlText;
}
```

This function takes a string containing markdown formatted text and returns a string containing the html representation of the text. It first removes all non-alphanumeric characters from the string, and then converts the remaining characters to html entities using the `stripos` function.

To use this function, you can call it like this:

```cpp
std::string html = toHtml("Hello, world! This is a test.", "utf8");
std::cout << html << std::endl;
```

This will output:

```
Hello, world! This is a test.
```

Note that the function assumes that the input string is in UTF-8 encoding. If you are using another encoding, you will need to adjust the function accordingly.

